question.question_text: Will electric vehicles make up more than 10% of new light duty vehicle sales in the United States before October 2025?
question.resolution_criteria: This question resolves as **Yes** if sales of battery electric vehicles (BEV) exceed 10% of total light-duty vehicle sales (LDV) in the United States for any complete month before the sales figures reported for October 2025, according to [Argonne National Laboratory's Light Duty Electric Drive Vehicles Monthly Sales Updates - Historical Data](https://www.anl.gov/esia/reference/light-duty-electric-drive-vehicles-monthly-sales-updates-historical-data). If this does not occur, this question resolves as **No**.
question.background_info:
According to [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-03-28/electric-cars-pass-adoption-tipping-point-in-31-countries?srnd=green), once 5% of new car sales are fully electric, it can be a pivotal tipping point, signaling the start of mass adoption of a new technology:

> New technologies — from televisions to smartwatches — follow an S-shaped adoption curve. Sales move at a crawl during the early-adopter phase, before hooking into a wave of mainstream acceptance. The transition often hinges on overcoming initial barriers such as cost, a lack of infrastructure and consumer skepticism. The tipping point signals the flattening of these barriers. While each country’s journey to 5% plays out differently, timelines converge in the years that follow.

> “Once enough sales occur, you kind of have a virtuous cycle,” said Corey Cantor, an EV analyst at BloombergNEF. “More EVs popping up means more people seeing them as mainstream, automakers more willing to invest in the market, and the charging infrastructure expanding on a good trajectory.

# SUMMARY
*Question*: Will electric vehicles make up more than 10% of new light duty vehicle sales in the United States before October 2025?

### Research Summary
Here's a concise rundown of the most relevant information regarding electric vehicle (EV) sales in the United States:

- As of January 2025, EV market share reached 9.1% of U.S. retail sales, according to J.D. Power data [1].

- Cox Automotive projects that 25% of U.S. car sales in 2025 will be EVs or hybrids, with full EVs climbing to 10% [12].

- In Q4 2024, EV sales in the U.S. increased by 15.2% year-over-year to 365,824 units, setting a new volume record [5].

- For the full year 2024, 1.3 million EVs were sold in the U.S., a 7.3% increase from 2023 [5].

- Rho Motion forecasts that EV sales in the USA & Canada will reach 2.1 million units in 2025, a 16% growth rate [7].

- However, policy uncertainty under the new administration could impact EV growth, with potential rollbacks on tax credits and emissions regulations [5][7].

- Despite this, consumer interest in EVs remains strong, with 64% of global survey respondents likely to consider an EV as their next purchase [5].

- The average cost of EVs is decreasing, narrowing the price gap with conventional vehicles [5].

Based on current trends and projections, it appears likely that EVs will surpass 10% of new light duty vehicle sales in the U.S. before October 2025. However, the question has not definitively resolved yet, as policy changes and market fluctuations could still impact the outcome.


# RESEARCH
## Report 1 Research
Here's a concise rundown of the most relevant information regarding electric vehicle (EV) sales in the United States:

- As of January 2025, EV market share reached 9.1% of U.S. retail sales, according to J.D. Power data [1].

- Cox Automotive projects that 25% of U.S. car sales in 2025 will be EVs or hybrids, with full EVs climbing to 10% [12].

- In Q4 2024, EV sales in the U.S. increased by 15.2% year-over-year to 365,824 units, setting a new volume record [5].

- For the full year 2024, 1.3 million EVs were sold in the U.S., a 7.3% increase from 2023 [5].

- Rho Motion forecasts that EV sales in the USA & Canada will reach 2.1 million units in 2025, a 16% growth rate [7].

- However, policy uncertainty under the new administration could impact EV growth, with potential rollbacks on tax credits and emissions regulations [5][7].

- Despite this, consumer interest in EVs remains strong, with 64% of global survey respondents likely to consider an EV as their next purchase [5].

- The average cost of EVs is decreasing, narrowing the price gap with conventional vehicles [5].

Based on current trends and projections, it appears likely that EVs will surpass 10% of new light duty vehicle sales in the U.S. before October 2025. However, the question has not definitively resolved yet, as policy changes and market fluctuations could still impact the outcome.


# FORECASTS

## R1: Forecaster 1 Reasoning
Before answering the question, let's consider the following:

(a) **Time left until the outcome is known:** There are approximately 7 months remaining until October 2025. This is the period during which BEV sales must exceed 10% of total light-duty vehicle sales in the U.S. for any complete month to resolve the question as "Yes."

(b) **Status quo outcome if nothing changed:** As of January 2025, the EV market share in the U.S. was 9.1%. If this share remains constant or does not reach 10% in any month before October 2025, the outcome would be "No."

(c) **Scenario that results in a No outcome:** A scenario leading to a "No" outcome could involve policy changes under the new administration that negatively impact EV growth, such as rollbacks on tax credits and emissions regulations. Additionally, if supply chain disruptions or economic downturns occur, they could slow the growth of EV sales, preventing them from reaching the 10% threshold.

(d) **Scenario that results in a Yes outcome:** A "Yes" outcome could occur if the current growth trend continues or accelerates. Factors contributing to this could include increased consumer interest in EVs, further reductions in EV costs, expansion of charging infrastructure, and potential new incentives or policies favoring EV adoption. If these factors align, it's plausible that EV sales could surpass 10% of total light-duty vehicle sales in a given month before October 2025.

**Rationale:**
Given the current trajectory and the fact that EV market share has already reached 9.1%, the likelihood of surpassing the 10% threshold in the next few months seems reasonable. The growth in EV sales, as evidenced by the 15.2% year-over-year increase in Q4 2024, supports this. However, it's also important to consider potential policy changes and market fluctuations that could hinder this growth. Nonetheless, the overall trend and projections suggest a favorable outcome for reaching the 10% mark.

**Final Answer:**
Probability: 75%

question.question_text: Will Elon Musk be the world's richest person on December 31, 2025?
question.resolution_criteria: This question resolves as **Yes** if, according to the [Bloomberg Billionaires Index](https://www.bloomberg.com/billionaires/), Elon Musk is ranked #1 in net worth when the resolution source is accessed by Metaculus on December 31, 2025. If Musk is not ranked #1, then this question resolves as **No**.
question.fine_print:
* If both Elon Musk and another individual are ranked #1, this resolves as **No**.
* If the Billionaires Index is not available on December 31, 2025, this question will be resolved as the first day for which it is available. If it is not available before January 4, 2026, this question will be **annulled**.
* Bloomberg outlines its methodology [here](https://www.bloomberg.com/billionaires/methodology/).
* In the event of Bloomberg changing its methodology for calculating the net worths of the individuals on its list, Admins will make a determination about whether the change is substantial enough to annul the question, at their discretion.
question.background_info:
Bloomberg maintains its [Real-Time Billionaires list](https://www.bloomberg.com/billionaires/), which is a tracker that is updated every day, ranking the world's wealthiest individuals based on net worth. In recent years, the list [has been topped](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_World%27s_Billionaires) by Bernard Arnault & family, Jeff Bezos, and Bill Gates. As of December 20, 2024, Elon Musk is in first place on the list, with \$455 billion, as compared with Jeff Bezos in second place with \$242 billion, Mark Zuckerberg in third place with \$211 billion, and Larry Ellison in fourth place with \$190 billion.

Elon Musk's wealth comes first and primarily from his shares of [Tesla](https://www.tesla.com/). According to Tesla's [proxy statement for 2024](https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1318605/000110465924048040/tm2326076d13_pre14a.htm), Musk beneficially owned 20.5% of Tesla's shares. With a [market cap](https://companiesmarketcap.com/tesla/marketcap/) at the time of this question of  1.249 Trillion, his stake in Tesla is worth 256 billion.

Secondly, Elon Musk [reportedly owns](https://www.the-independent.com/news/world/americas/musk-net-worth-spacex-trump-b2660290.html) 42% of [SpaceX](https://www.spacex.com/), which was recently valued at \$210 billion. This stake is worth \$88 billion, at that valuation. Additional stakes owned by Musk are 54%of [xAI](https://x.ai/), a startup valued at 50 billion; [Neuralink](https://neuralink.com/), which was valued at \$5 billion; the [Boring Company](http://www.boringcompany.com/), valued at \$5.68 billion in 2022, and, X (formerly Twitter), which was [recently valued](https://www.axios.com/2024/12/01/elon-musk-x-fidelity-mark-up) at about \$12 billion.

***
